    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-09-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-09-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="166" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 166.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Scruggs</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Bogota</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-09-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 17, 1885</date>.
                            (Received October 26.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 234.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The capture of the rebel flotilla and the
                        opening of the Magdalena River to navigation, as reported in my No. 230, of
                        the 29th August last, is now confirmed by official reports. The report of
                        the capture of Ricardo Gaitan, the “general” in command of the rebel forces
                        on the river, was, however, premature. It was another Gaitan who was
                        captured. Ricardo made his escape, and is now supposed to be somewhere in
                        the State of Antioquia.</p>
                <pb facs="0348" n="220" xml:id="pg_220"/>
                <p>With the exception of a few small bands of guerrillas in the remote districts
                        (which are rapidly disappearing) the civil war is considered over for the
                        present. I say “for the present,” because there seems to be a very general
                        impression here that we are to have another “revolution” soon. * * * *</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM L. SCRUGGS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
